This practical is based on RMI (Remote Method Invocation) in Java.

RMI allows a program running on one computer (client) to call methods of another program running on another computer (server) as if the method is local.

In this practical:

The client sends two strings to the server.
The server performs concatenation (joins the strings).
The server sends the result back to the client.

Example:

Client sends: "Hello" and "World"
Server returns: "HelloWorld"





Main Concept of RMI

RMI is used for communication between distributed systems.

It follows the Client-Server Architecture.

Components:
Client
Requests service
Sends two strings
Server
Provides service
Concatenates strings
Remote Interface
Contains methods that client can call remotely
RMI Registry
Stores remote objects
Helps client locate server object






1. Distributed Application

An application where components run on different systems but communicate through network.

2. RMI

Remote Method Invocation.

Used in Java to call methods from remote machines.


3. Remote Interface

Defines methods that can be accessed remotely by client.


4. Stub

Acts like a proxy for remote object on client side.

Client communicates with stub instead of actual server object.



5. Skeleton (Old Concept)

Receives request from stub and passes it to server object.

(In modern Java versions, skeleton is internally handled.)



6. RMI Registry

A naming service where remote objects are registered.

Default port:

1099
